    mechanism:
      "**L-ascorbic acid** — a water-soluble vitamin that humans cannot synthesize endogenously due to evolutionary loss of the L-gulonolactone oxidase (GULO) gene; the dietary requirement reflects this genetic loss rather than a fundamental cellular dependence on dietary vitamin C across mammals (most mammals synthesize ascorbic acid in liver from glucose). Vitamin C must be obtained from diet (citrus, peppers, leafy greens, organ meats — particularly adrenal glands) or supplementation. **Mechanism — direct antioxidant via electron donation (the foundational role)**: ascorbic acid is a potent water-soluble antioxidant that donates electrons to neutralize reactive oxygen species (ROS) and reactive nitrogen species (RNS). The antioxidant reaction produces dehydroascorbic acid (oxidized form), which is then reduced back to ascorbic acid by glutathione-dependent reduction (via dehydroascorbate reductase) and other cellular reductases. The **glutathione partnership** is mechanistically significant — vitamin C and glutathione recycle each other in cellular antioxidant defense; supplementation of either supports the other's effective antioxidant activity. **Mechanism — collagen synthesis cofactor (the connective tissue role)**: ascorbic acid is the obligate cofactor for prolyl 4-hydroxylase and lysyl hydroxylase — enzymes that hydroxylate proline and lysine residues in nascent procollagen chains. The hydroxylation creates the structural basis for collagen triple helix formation and intermolecular cross-linking; without adequate vitamin C, collagen synthesis produces structurally inadequate collagen with broad consequences for connective tissue (skin, blood vessel walls, bone matrix, tendon/ligament). The historical disease scurvy reflects severe vitamin C deficiency producing collagen synthesis failure — bleeding gums, easy bruising, joint pain, slow wound healing, and ultimately fatal hemorrhage. **Mechanism — catecholamine synthesis cofactor**: ascorbic acid is cofactor for dopamine β-hydroxylase (the enzyme converting dopamine to norepinephrine in adrenal medulla and noradrenergic neurons) and partly involved in tyrosine hydroxylase regulation. The catecholamine synthesis role is part of why adrenal gland tissue concentrates vitamin C at among the highest levels in the body. **Mechanism — carnitine biosynthesis cofactor**: ascorbic acid is cofactor for hydroxylation steps in carnitine biosynthesis (lysine → carnitine pathway). Severe vitamin C deficiency can produce carnitine insufficiency contributing to the fatigue and weakness characteristic of scurvy. **Mechanism — iron absorption enhancement**: ascorbic acid reduces ferric (Fe3+) iron to ferrous (Fe2+) iron in the GI lumen, substantially enhancing non-heme iron absorption from plant-source foods. Practical implication: vitamin C with iron-rich plant foods (spinach, beans, lentils) supports iron absorption; users with iron overload conditions (hemochromatosis) should be cautious about high-dose vitamin C with iron-rich meals. **Mechanism — multi-route bioavailability profile (the form-selection centerpiece)**: vitamin C bioavailability varies substantially by route and formulation: **(1) Oral ascorbic acid** — saturable absorption via SVCT1/SVCT2 transporters; bioavailability ~98% at 100mg, declining to ~25% at 5g; plasma saturation around 1.5-2g/day oral; **bowel tolerance** is the practical dose limit — GI tolerance dose varies substantially across users (typically 1-10g/day with substantial individual variance); at saturation, additional oral dose produces minimal plasma elevation. **(2) Buffered ascorbates** (sodium ascorbate, calcium ascorbate, magnesium ascorbate) — slightly easier on GI; useful for users with sensitive stomachs; same fundamental absorption ceiling as ascorbic acid. **(3) Liposomal vitamin C** — phospholipid encapsulation enables transport via different absorption mechanism; **substantially exceeds oral saturation ceiling**; achieves higher peak plasma levels than equivalent oral ascorbic acid; well-tolerated GI; the practical upgrade for users wanting higher plasma exposure without IV. **(4) IV ascorbic acid** — bypasses absorption entirely; achieves millimolar plasma concentrations unattainable orally (10-25 mM at high doses); used in integrative oncology and infectious disease contexts; clinical infusion setting. **(5) Ester-C** — proprietary calcium ascorbate + dehydroascorbate + ascorbate metabolites; mild absorption advantage marketing claims; modest evidence base; not substantially different from buffered ascorbate. **Mechanism — Linus Pauling mega-dose protocol (the high-dose framework)**: Linus Pauling (Nobel laureate chemistry, peace) proposed mega-dose vitamin C (10g+ daily oral) as foundational health intervention, including infectious disease prevention, cancer adjunct, and cardiovascular support (the **Pauling protocol** combining vitamin C + lysine for Lp(a) reduction — based on hypothesis that Lp(a) deposits in lysine-binding sites of damaged vessel walls; vitamin C supports vessel wall collagen integrity; lysine competes for Lp(a) binding sites). The Pauling protocol has mechanistic plausibility but modest clinical evidence base; mainstream cardiology has not adopted it. The mega-dose oral approach is limited by saturable absorption — the practical ceiling for oral mega-dosing is bowel tolerance and plasma saturation regardless of dose target. **Pharmaceutical status**: vitamin C is widely available as over-the-counter dietary supplement; FDA-approved as Acidulin (compounded; rare clinical use). IV ascorbic acid is available as compounded preparation via integrative medicine compounding pharmacies for clinical use. **Pharmacokinetics**: plasma half-life ~30 minutes; oral peak 2-3 hours post-dose; IV peak immediate.",
