    mechanism:
      "**Essential trace mineral** that functions as the cofactor for approximately 25 selenoproteins encoded in the human genome — proteins that incorporate selenium as the unique amino acid **selenocysteine** (the '21st amino acid') at specific functional positions. The selenocysteine residue's selenol group is substantially more reactive than cysteine's thiol group, providing distinctive redox catalysis capabilities for selenoenzyme functions. The selenoprotein family roles span antioxidant defense, thyroid hormone metabolism, protein repair, and selenium transport. **Mechanism — glutathione peroxidase cofactor (the principal antioxidant role)**: the glutathione peroxidase (GPx) family — GPx1 through GPx8 with tissue-specific expression — uses glutathione (GSH) as electron donor to reduce hydrogen peroxide and lipid peroxides to water and the corresponding alcohols. **GPx is one of the principal enzymatic antioxidant defenses in human cells, and selenium is the obligate cofactor at the selenocysteine active site.** The GPx-NAC-glutathione pathway is integrated: NAC supplies cysteine for endogenous glutathione synthesis; glutathione donates electrons via GPx to neutralize peroxides; selenium is the GPx cofactor enabling the reaction. Selenium status directly affects glutathione peroxidase activity and therefore the antioxidant pathway's effectiveness. **Mechanism — thyroid deiodinase cofactor (the T4 → T3 conversion role)**: iodothyronine deiodinases (DIO1, DIO2, DIO3) are selenoenzymes that catalyze the deiodination steps in thyroid hormone metabolism — most importantly the conversion of inactive thyroxine (T4) to active triiodothyronine (T3). **DIO2 in peripheral tissues drives most cellular T3 from T4** — making selenium a critical cofactor for thyroid hormone activation. Selenium deficiency impairs T4 → T3 conversion regardless of TSH/T4 status; users may have 'normal' TSH and T4 on labs but functional hypothyroidism from inadequate T3 conversion. The selenium-thyroid axis explains why selenium supplementation often produces noticeable subjective improvement (energy, mood, body temperature, metabolism) in users with subclinical thyroid issues. **Mechanism — Hashimoto's autoimmunity context**: clinical research has demonstrated that selenium supplementation (typically selenomethionine 200mcg/day) reduces thyroid peroxidase (TPO) antibody levels in users with Hashimoto's autoimmune thyroiditis. Mechanism candidates include enhanced GPx activity reducing thyroid oxidative stress, modulation of T-regulatory cell function, and direct selenoprotein effects on autoimmune signaling. The Hashimoto's antibody reduction effect is one of the better-established clinical applications of selenium supplementation. **Mechanism — thioredoxin reductase and other selenoproteins**: thioredoxin reductases (TrxR1-3) are selenoenzymes maintaining the thioredoxin antioxidant system parallel to the glutathione system; methionine sulfoxide reductase B1 (MsrB1) repairs oxidatively damaged methionine residues; selenoprotein P serves as the principal selenium transport protein in plasma; selenoprotein N is important for muscle function. The combined selenoprotein family extends selenium's role beyond GPx and deiodinases. **Mechanism — multiple form options (the form-selection consideration)**: selenium supplementation forms have substantially different bioavailability and incorporation profiles: **(1) Selenomethionine (Se-Met)** — the principal organic form found in food (selenium-enriched yeast, Brazil nuts, organ meats); high bioavailability; **incorporated nonspecifically into proteins** in place of methionine, providing tissue selenium reservoir but also non-targeted incorporation; preferred form for most supplementation; standard pattern is selenium-yeast or pure L-selenomethionine. **(2) Sodium selenite (Na2SeO3)** — inorganic form; less bioavailable than selenomethionine; primarily incorporated into selenocysteine via the dedicated selenocysteine biosynthesis pathway (more direct pathway to functional selenoproteins); some integrative medicine practitioners argue selenite provides better functional selenoprotein support despite lower total bioavailability; the comparison is debated. **(3) Sodium selenate (Na2SeO4)** — inorganic; less commonly used. **(4) Selenocysteine (Se-Cys)** — direct cofactor form; rare in supplements; expensive. **(5) Selenium-enriched yeast** — selenomethionine-dominant; standardized branded products (SelenoExcell, SelenoPrecise) provide quality assurance. **Mechanism — Brazil nut natural source variability**: Brazil nuts are a natural concentrated selenium source — but with substantial variability (one Brazil nut can deliver 90-540 mcg depending on soil selenium content where the tree was grown). Brazil nuts from selenium-rich soils (parts of Brazil, Bolivia) are concentrated; nuts from selenium-poor soils provide less. The variability makes Brazil nuts an unreliable supplementation strategy — 2-3 Brazil nuts daily can range from adequate (200-400mcg) to overdose (800-1500mcg) depending on source. **Pharmaceutical status**: selenium is widely available as over-the-counter dietary supplement; not an FDA-approved pharmaceutical for any indication. **Pharmacokinetics**: oral bioavailability good for selenomethionine (~90%); plasma half-life days; tissue accumulation in protein-bound selenomethionine reservoir; toxicity threshold (selenosis) at sustained intakes >400mcg/day from all sources combined.",
